            "content": "# Syscall Fast-Path Acceleration\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\nkbox intercepts guest syscalls and routes them to an in-process Linux kernel\n(LKL).  Three interception tiers trade isolation for speed:\n\n| Tier | Mechanism | Latency | When used |\n|------|-----------|---------|-----------|\n| 3 | seccomp USER_NOTIF | ~13-47us | Shell commands, --net, --syscall-mode=seccomp |\n| 1 | SIGSYS trap (RET_TRAP) | ~16-23us | Trap fallback when rewrite infeasible |\n| 2 | Binary rewriting | ~1.6-17us | Non-shell direct binaries (AUTO default) |\n\nAUTO mode selects the fastest available tier per command:\n- Shell commands (sh, bash, ash, etc.) → seccomp (fork/exec coherence)\n- Commands with --net → seccomp (SLIRP requires supervisor poll loop)\n- Non-shell, non-net binaries → rewrite (with trap and seccomp fallbacks)\n\n## Dispatch Pipeline\n\n```\nGuest syscall instruction\n    │\n    ├── [rewrite] SVC/syscall patched to B/JMP → trampoline\n    │       │\n    │       ├── local fast-path (kbox_dispatch_try_local_fast_path)\n    │       │     ├── Tier 1: pure emulation (getpid=1, getppid=0, gettid=1)\n    │       │     └── Tier 2: always-CONTINUE (50 syscalls → host kernel)\n    │       │\n    │       └── service thread (futex IPC → kbox_dispatch_request → LKL)\n    │\n    ├── [trap] BPF returns RET_TRAP → SIGSYS handler\n    │       │\n    │       ├── local fast-path (same as above)\n    │       └── service thread (same as above)\n    │\n    └── [seccomp] BPF returns USER_NOTIF → supervisor process\n            └── kbox_dispatch_request → LKL → ioctl response\n```\n\n## Changes (vs commit 47157b2)\n\n19 files changed, 634 insertions, 181 deletions.\n\n### 1. Direct guest memory access with fault recovery (procmem.c)\n\n**Problem**: In trap/rewrite mode (same address space), `kbox_current_read`,\n`kbox_current_write`, and `kbox_current_read_string` used\n`pread(/proc/self/mem)` and `process_vm_writev`.  The BPF filter's IP gate\nblocked these syscalls with EPERM (kbox text segment IPs not in registered\ntrampoline ranges), causing stat to SKIP in rewrite mode on aarch64.\n\n**Fix**: Replace with direct `memcpy` wrapped in `sigsetjmp`/`siglongjmp`\nfault recovery.  Three levels of optimization were applied:\n\n1. Initial: per-call `sigaction` save/restore (~3us overhead per call).\n2. Generation counter: install fault handler once, reinstall only when\n   guest modifies SIGSEGV/SIGBUS via `rt_sigaction`.  Handler saved via\n   `sigaction(&sa, &saved_guest_segv)` and chained for non-memcpy faults.\n3. `sigsetjmp(fault_jmp, 0)`: the `0` flag skips the `rt_sigprocmask`\n   syscall that `sigsetjmp(..., 1)` performs per call.  This eliminated\n   the x86_64 regression where rewrite stat was slower than seccomp.\n\nThe final hot path per `safe_memcpy` call is: one atomic load (generation\ncheck) + `sigsetjmp` (no syscalls) + `memcpy` + two `fault_armed` stores.\nSub-microsecond overhead.\n\n- Unmapped guest pointers return `-EFAULT` via `siglongjmp` recovery\n- Guest signal handlers are preserved and forwarded (`SA_SIGINFO` chaining)\n- `kbox_procmem_signal_changed()` bumps the generation on guest\n  `rt_sigaction(SIGSEGV/SIGBUS)` dispatch\n\n### 2. Guest-thread local fast-path (seccomp-dispatch.c)\n\n**Problem**: All trap/rewrite dispatches went through the service thread via\nfutex IPC, even for syscalls that never touch LKL.\n\n**Fix**: New `kbox_dispatch_try_local_fast_path()` called before the service\nthread handoff in both `direct_trap_execute` and `rewrite_dispatch_request`.\n\nTier 1 -- pure emulation (zero overhead):\n- `getpid` → 1, `getppid` → 0, `gettid` → 1\n\nTier 2 -- always-CONTINUE (host kernel handles directly, no IPC):\n- brk, futex, rseq, set_tid_address, set_robust_list\n- munmap, mremap, membarrier, madvise\n- wait4, waitid, exit, exit_group\n- rt_sigreturn, rt_sigaltstack, setitimer, getitimer\n- setpgid, getpgid, getsid, setsid, fork, vfork\n- sched_yield, sched_setparam, sched_getparam, sched_setscheduler,\n  sched_getscheduler, sched_get_priority_max, sched_get_priority_min,\n  sched_setaffinity, sched_getaffinity\n- getrlimit, getrusage\n- epoll_create1, epoll_ctl, epoll_wait, epoll_pwait\n- ppoll, pselect6, poll\n- nanosleep, clock_nanosleep\n- timerfd_create, timerfd_settime, timerfd_gettime\n- eventfd, eventfd2\n- statfs, fstatfs, sysinfo\n\nAll 50 entries verified unconditional in `kbox_dispatch_request` (audited\nby Codex across multiple review rounds).\n\n### 3. Removed unsafe guest-thread LKL dispatch (rewrite.c)\n\nLKL requires its own thread context.  The old wrapper fast-path called\n`forward_newfstatat`, `forward_openat`, etc. directly on the guest thread,\nracing with the service thread and crashing under sustained load on aarch64.\nRemoved entirely; service thread failure is a hard error.\n\n### 4. Spin-then-futex IPC (syscall-trap.c)\n\nBoth `wait_for_pending_dispatch` (guest side) and `trap_service_thread_main`\n(service side) spin 1024 iterations with `pause` (x86_64) / `yield`\n(aarch64) before falling back to `futex(FUTEX_WAIT_PRIVATE)`.\n\n### 5. SQPOLL mode (--sqpoll)\n\nService thread busy-polls without futex fallback.  Available for\nlatency-sensitive workloads.  No measurable improvement over the 1024-spin\ndefault because LKL dispatch time dominates the futex scheduling cost.\n\n### 6. AUTO mode enabled (image.c)\n\n`KBOX_AUTO_ENABLE_USERSPACE_FAST_PATH` set to 1.  AUTO selects rewrite/trap\nfor non-shell, non-net commands.  aarch64 cancel-wrapper override removed.\n\n### 7. P0 correctness bugs fixed\n\n- **CLOEXEC rollback on failed execve**: replaced destructive\n  `kbox_fd_table_close_cloexec` with `kbox_fd_table_clear_cloexec_flags`\n  that clears the flag without closing entries.\n- **Mount/umount path translation bypass**: `forward_mount` target,\n  `forward_umount2` path, and bind-mount source now routed through\n  `kbox_translate_path_for_lkl`.\n- **MAP_SHARED writes on shadow FDs**: memfds created with\n  `MFD_ALLOW_SE