            "new_string": "### Remaining (Post-P6)",
            "old_string": "### Design Concept\n\nA pixel-art \"kernel house\" cross-section occupies the left/center of the\ndashboard. Each room represents a kernel subsystem. Penguin characters move\nbetween rooms as syscalls flow through the system. The existing telemetry\npanels (charts, gauges, event feed) remain on the right side or in tabs.\n\n```\n┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  User Space (attic)                             │\n│  [guest process penguins making syscalls]       │\n├─────────────────────────────────────────────────┤\n│  Syscall Gate                                   │\n│  [seccomp-unotify desk, penguin dispatcher]     │\n├──────────┬───────────┬──────────┬───────────────┤\n│ VFS Room │ Process   │ Memory   │ Network       │\n│ [filing  │ Mgmt      │ Mgmt     │ [mailroom     │\n│  cabinet │ [scheduler│[page     │  penguins,    │\n│  penguin]│  penguin] │ penguin] │  SLIRP desk]  │\n├──────────┴───────────┴──────────┴───────────────┤\n│  Block I/O Basement (dimmed, no data yet)       │\n│  [placeholder -- activates post-P6]             │\n└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘\n```\n\n### Rooms (Subsystems) and What Drives Them\n\nEach room lights up / shows activity based on real kbox telemetry:\n\nRooms use two data channels: (1) SSE sampled events trigger individual\ncharacter animations (penguin walks, speech bubbles); (2) `/api/snapshot`\naggregate deltas drive ambient room state (glow intensity, stack height,\nbusyness level). SSE is lossy by design -- rooms must look alive from\nsnapshot deltas alone even if no sampled events arrive.\n\n| Room | Subsystem | Ambient source (snapshot) | Animation source (SSE) | Activity trigger |\n|------|-----------|--------------------------|------------------------|------------------|\n| Attic | User space | counters.syscall_total rate | sampled syscall events (pid, name) | Any syscall from guest |\n| Gate | seccomp dispatch | counters.disp_continue/return/enosys | sampled syscall events (disp field) | Every intercepted syscall |\n| VFS | Virtual filesystem | family.file_io + family.dir rates | sampled syscall events where family=file_io or dir | open, read, write, stat, readdir |\n| Process | Scheduler/process | context_switches rate (ambience only, not per-PID) | sampled syscall events where family=scheduler | clone, execve, exit |\n| Memory | Memory management | mem.total - mem.free, pgfault, pgmajfault | sampled syscall events where family=memory | mmap, brk, page faults |\n| Network | Networking | family.other rate (socket calls land here) | sampled syscall events where family=other and nr matches socket/connect/sendmsg | socket, connect, sendmsg |\n| Basement | Block I/O | DEFERRED (no data source yet) | DEFERRED | Needs block counters in backend |\n| FD Vault | FD table | fd.used, fd.max | sampled syscall events where family=fd_ops | open, close, dup2, pipe |\n\nBackend data notes:\n- All SSE events are type `\"syscall\"` -- no `\"process\"` event type exists.\n  The frontend subscribes to `process` events but the backend never emits\n  them (dead code). Process room animation relies on classifying incoming\n  syscall events by family=scheduler, not on a separate event type.\n- Memory snapshot is nested: `mem.total`, `mem.free`, `mem.available`,\n  `mem.buffers`, `mem.cached`, `mem.slab`. Compute used as\n  `mem.total - mem.free`. No `mem_used` field exists.\n- FD snapshot is nested: `fd.used`, `fd.max`.\n- Network has no dedicated family. Socket/connect/sendmsg syscalls fall\n  into `family.other` alongside miscellaneous calls. To distinguish\n  network activity, the scene must check `nr` (syscall number) against\n  a known set of network syscall numbers when family=other.\n- The `args[6]` array exists in the event struct (web.h) but is NOT\n  serialized to the SSE JSON payload. Only `name`, `nr`, `pid`, `disp`,\n  `ret`, `err`, `lat_ns` are available client-side.\n\nNote: The Basement room appears in the scene layout as a dimmed/inactive\nroom from day one, but is not wired to telemetry until block I/O counters\nare added to `web-telemetry.c` (separate backend task, not part of P6).\nFile read/write syscalls animate VFS, not Basement -- page cache means\nmost file I/O never hits the block layer.\n\n### Character Design\n\nStart with ONE base penguin sprite sheet (7x3 frames: idle/walk/type/\ncelebrate/error/sleep, 3 directions), reusing tinyclaw's frame layout.\nRole differentiation via small accessory overlays (hat, folder, stopwatch)\ndrawn as separate sprite strips and composited at render time. This avoids\ndrawing 7 full sprite sheets upfront and lets us iterate on the base\npenguin design first.\n\n| Character | Role | Accessory overlay |\n|-----------|------|-------------------|\n| Dispatcher Tux | seccomp gate | Sorting hat |\n| File Tux | VFS operations | Folder |\n| Sched Tux | Process scheduler | Stopwatch |\n| Memory Tux | Page allocator | Memory block |\n| Net Tux | Network stack | Envelope |\n| Storage Tux | Block I/O / ext4 | DEFERRED (room inactive) |\n| Guest penguin(s) | Tracee processes | None (smaller, lighter color variant) |\n\nGuest penguins are pooled: cap at 6-8 visible simultaneously. When more\nPIDs are active, a \"crowd\" indicator (count badge) appears in the Attic.\nWhen one penguin exits the Gate, the next \"steps forward\" from the crowd.\n\nSpeech bubbles (tinyclaw-style) show what is happening. V1 scope is\nlimited to data available in the SSE event payload -- syscall name,\ndisposition, and latency. Pathname/argument narration (e.g.,\n\"openat(/etc/passwd)\") requires a future `args_summary` field in\n`web-events.c` with a redaction policy; do NOT implement in P6.\n\nV1 bubble examples:\n- Dispatcher: \"openat → VFS Room\" (name + target room)\n- File Tux: \"read, 15.2us\" (name + latency)\n- Sched Tux: \"context switch\" (ambient, from snapshot delta)\n- Error state: Red shake animation + \"ENOSYS: fadvise64\"\n\n### Implementation Plan\n\nThree